issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: The fuel injectors in 1988-1991 Honda CRX Si models are prone to clogging and failure, particularly the injector for cylinder #3. This is often caused by fuel system contamination and age-related degradation of internal components.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed fuel injectors, clean fuel system, replace fuel filter
issues.prevention: Use quality fuel, replace fuel filter regularly, add fuel system cleaner periodically

issues.title: Distributor O-Ring Oil Leak
issues.description: The O-ring seal around the distributor housing commonly fails, allowing engine oil to leak into the distributor cap and rotor area. This can cause ignition problems and potential engine damage if not addressed.
issues.fix_description: Replace distributor O-ring seal, clean distributor components
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, inspect distributor area during maintenance

issues.title: Timing Belt Failure
issues.description: The B16A engine is an interference engine, meaning that timing belt failure will cause severe internal engine damage. The timing belt and water pump should be replaced as preventive maintenance every 60,000 miles.
issues.fix_description: Replace timing belt, water pump, tensioner; rebuild engine if damage occurred
issues.prevention: Replace timing belt every 60,000 miles or 7 years, inspect regularly

issues.title: CV Joint Failure
issues.description: The constant velocity joints, particularly the outer CV joints, are prone to premature wear due to torn CV joint boots allowing contamination and grease loss.
issues.fix_description: Replace CV joint assembly or entire axle shaft
issues.prevention: Inspect CV boots regularly, replace boots when torn to prevent contamination

issues.title: Main Relay Failure
issues.description: The main fuel pump relay is prone to failure due to heat-related solder joint cracking. This causes intermittent or complete fuel pump failure, leading to no-start conditions.
issues.fix_description: Replace main relay or re-solder relay connections
issues.prevention: Replace relay proactively, avoid exposing relay to excessive heat

issues.title: Window Regulator Failure
issues.description: The manual window regulators are prone to cable breakage and gear wear, causing windows to fall down into the door or become difficult to operate.
issues.fix_description: Replace window regulator assembly, lubricate window tracks
issues.prevention: Lubricate window mechanisms regularly, avoid forcing stuck windows

issues.title: Clutch Hydraulic System Failure
issues.description: The clutch master and slave cylinders commonly develop internal seal failure, causing clutch pedal to go to the floor and inability to shift gears.
issues.fix_description: Replace clutch master cylinder and/or slave cylinder, bleed hydraulic system
issues.prevention: Replace clutch fluid every 2-3 years, inspect for leaks regularly

issues.title: Crankshaft Position Sensor Failure
issues.description: The crankshaft position sensor in the distributor fails due to heat exposure and age, causing intermittent stalling and no-start conditions.
issues.fix_description: Replace crankshaft position sensor or entire distributor assembly
issues.prevention: Replace sensor proactively at high mileage, avoid overheating engine

issues.title: Radiator Failure
issues.description: The plastic end tanks on the original radiators become brittle with age and commonly crack, causing coolant leaks and potential overheating.
issues.fix_description: Replace radiator, flush cooling system, replace thermostat
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, avoid overheating, inspect for leaks

issues.title: Brake Master Cylinder Failure
issues.description: The brake master cylinder internal seals fail with age, causing brake fluid leaks and potential brake system failure. This is a safety-critical issue.
issues.fix_description: Replace brake master cylinder, bleed entire brake system
issues.prevention: Replace brake fluid every 2-3 years, inspect brake lines regularly

issues.title: VTEC Solenoid Failure
issues.description: The VTEC solenoid valve becomes clogged with oil sludge or fails electrically, preventing proper VTEC engagement and reducing engine performance at high RPM.
issues.fix_description: Replace VTEC solenoid, clean oil passages, change oil and filter
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with proper viscosity, avoid extended oil change intervals

issues.title: Suspension Bushings Deterioration
issues.description: The rubber suspension bushings, particularly the rear trailing arm bushings and front lower control arm bushings, deteriorate with age causing handling problems.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn suspension bushings, perform wheel alignment
issues.prevention: Inspect bushings during regular maintenance, replace when cracked or worn

editorial.tagline: The original VTEC lightweight sports car perfection
editorial.hero_blurb: The CRX Si represents Honda's purest expression of the lightweight sports car philosophy. With its revolutionary VTEC engine and featherweight chassis, it delivers an intoxicating blend of razor-sharp handling and screaming high-rev performance that defined a generation of enthusiasts.
editorial.essence: This is Honda engineering at its most focused - a 2,200-pound missile with a 160hp VTEC heart that transforms from mild-mannered daily driver to track weapon at 5,800 rpm. The CRX Si proves that power-to-weight ratio trumps raw horsepower every time.
editorial.heritage: Born from Honda's late-80s golden age of engineering excellence, the CRX Si evolved from the original CRX concept into a proper sports car with the addition of VTEC technology and aggressive suspension tuning, becoming the blueprint for every lightweight Honda performance car that followed.
editorial.design_philosophy: Engineers prioritized weight reduction above all else, creating a purposeful wedge shape with minimal overhangs and maximum structural rigidity. Every component was scrutinized for weight savings while maintaining the purity of the driving experience.
editorial.motorsport_history: Dominated SCCA autocross and road racing in its era, with privateer teams finding success in various touring car championships. The platform's inherent balance and tunability made it a favorite among grassroots racers worldwide.
editorial.engine_character: The B16A VTEC is a masterpiece of high-revving naturally aspirated engineering - docile and fuel-efficient below 5,800 rpm, then unleashing a savage secondary cam profile that screams to 8,000 rpm with an addictive metallic howl.
editorial.transmission_feel: The cable-operated 5-speed offers precise, mechanical engagement with short throws and perfectly spaced ratios. Each shift feels deliberate and connected, with a satisfying snick into every gear.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Neutral handling with a slight rear-bias that rewards skilled drivers. The short wheelbase makes it incredibly agile while the low center of gravity keeps it planted through corners, with minimal body roll and maximum feedback.
editorial.steering_feel: Unassisted rack-and-pinion steering delivers pure, unfiltered road feel with perfect weighting. Every surface imperfection and traction change is communicated directly to your fingertips with surgical precision.
editorial.brake_confidence: Four-wheel disc brakes provide strong, progressive stopping power with excellent pedal feel. The lightweight chassis means less mass to stop, resulting in impressive braking performance and fade resistance.
editorial.sound_signature: The VTEC crossover creates an unmistakable mechanical symphony - a civilized hum below 6,000 rpm that erupts into a race-car wail as it climbs toward redline, punctuated by the satisfying metallic clatter of valve train components.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who value handling precision over straight-line speed, weekend canyon carvers, autocross enthusiasts, and anyone who believes the best cars are the ones that make you work for their performance.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Highway cruisers seeking comfort, those needing significant cargo space or rear passenger accommodations, or drivers who prefer effortless low-end torque over high-rev thrills.
editorial.buyers_summary: Find the cleanest, most original example possible as rust and modifications can destroy the car's inherent balance. Maintenance records are crucial given the VTEC engine's need for proper oil changes and timing belt service.
pros: Legendary VTEC engine with 8,000 rpm redline
Timeless wedge design that still looks modern
cons: Rust-prone body panels and rear hatch
Minimal interior space and cargo capacity
best_for: Weekend canyon runs and spirited driving
